  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Php 2:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπειδή",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Only three times elsewhere in Paul. The difference between it and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπεί",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is tersely stated by Ell[7]. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ad loc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), who notes that it “involves the quasi-temporal reference which is supplied by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δή",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and thus expresses a thing that at once ensues (temporarily or causally) on the occurrence or realisation of another”.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπιπ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἦν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". A common N.T. construction. Perhaps the use of the imperfect may be due to Aramaic influence (see Schmid, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Atticismus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", iii., p. 113 ff.). In classical Greek it is fairly frequent with the perfect and pluperfect. See Kühner, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ausführl. Gramm.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ii., p. 35, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "n.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 3—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πάντας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Apostle wishes to disarm all prejudices against Epaphr.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀδημονῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". “In sore anguish.” In its two other occurrences in N.T. it describes the agony in Gethsemane. While not found in LXX (but several exx. in Symmachus) it occurs a few times in later Greek. The derivations usually given are doubtful.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἠκούσατε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Probably we must suppose that the Philippians, on hearing that Epaphrod. was ill, had written a letter to which ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "this",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is the answer.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἠσθένησε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". We might translate, “had fallen sick,” an ingressive aorist. But with the same tense in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Php 2:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
