  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Here lay the “necessity,” in St Paul’s view, of his friend’s return to the Philippians; in Epaphroditus’ longing for them, and their love and anxiety in regard of him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he longed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The Greek is full and emphatic, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "he was (in a state of) longing",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", of home-sickness. See note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Php 1:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—Doubtless the feeling was a recent if not a present one; and in an English letter we should say accordingly, “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he has been",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in a home-sick condition.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "after you all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] A reading which has considerable support is “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to see you all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".” The precise phrase thus formed occurs ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 3:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 1:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Perhaps this is a reason for deciding against it here, as it might be a transcriber’s reminiscence.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Observe the still recurring “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "you all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".” Epaphroditus may have been in some way involved in those differences between sets and circles at Philippi (see above, on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Php 1:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.) which gave St Paul anxiety. So he emphasizes Epaphroditus’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "impartial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " affection for them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "full of heaviness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Better, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "[has been] sore troubled",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word is used of our blessed Lord’s “sore trouble” in the Garden, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 14:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". By derivation (see Lightfoot here) it probably suggests the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "restlessness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of profound ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "dislike",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", shrinking from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "loathed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " pain or grief.—We see a character of great sensitiveness and tenderness.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ye had heard",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.] An English letter-writer would more naturally, say ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "you have heard that he has been ill",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The reference is to comparative recency, and present results. See Introduction, p. 16.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
